  `product_warehouse` (`cost`, `price`, `product_id`, `qty`, `warehouse_id`)
values
  (50, 200, 220, 100, 100),
  (50, 200, 220, 100, 200),
  (50, 200, 220, 100, 50)

foreach ($this->productWarehouse as $key => $warehouseId) {
            $this->product->warehouses()->attach($warehouseId, [
                'price' => $this->productWarehouse[$key]['price'],
                'cost'  => $this->productWarehouse[$key]['cost'],
                'qty'   => $this->productWarehouse[$key]['quantity'],
            ]);
        } //  public function warehouses()
    {
        return $this->belongsToMany(Warehouse::class)
        ->withPivot('price', 'qty','cost');
    }

The error you are encountering occurs because the insert statement is trying to add a product_warehouse record with a warehouse_id that does not exist in the `warehouses` table. In other words, there is a foreign key constraint that requires the warehouse_id in the product_warehouse table to reference a valid id in the warehouses table.

To resolve this issue, ensure that the warehouse_id values in the insert statement actually exist in the warehouses table. If they do not exist, you will need to either create the appropriate warehouse records or update the warehouse_id values in the insert statement to reference valid warehouse ids.

You can modify your code by adding a check to make sure the warehouse_id exists in the warehouse table before attaching it to the Product:

```php
foreach ($this->productWarehouse as $key => $warehouseId) {
    // Check if the Warehouse exists in the database
    $warehouse = Warehouse::find($warehouseId);
    if ($warehouse) {
        $this->product->warehouses()->attach($warehouseId, [
            'price' => $this->productWarehouse[$key]['price'],
            'cost'  => $this->productWarehouse[$key]['cost'],
            'qty'   => $this->productWarehouse[$key]['quantity'],
        ]);
    } else {
        // Handle the case when the warehouse doesn't exist, e.g. log an error or show a message
    }
}
```

