One common use case for the crossbeam crate is implementing concurrent data structures, such as queues or hash tables. For example, let's say we need to implement a thread-safe hash table in Rust. We can use the `HashMap` data structure provided by the standard library, but we'll need to synchronize access to the `HashMap` to ensure it can be safely accessed by multiple threads.

We can use the crossbeam crate to do this by creating a global `Arc<HashMap>` instance that all threads can access. We'll also create a `Mutex` to protect the `HashMap` from concurrent access and a `Condvar` to notify waiting threads whenever the `HashMap` is updated.

Here's an example code that uses the `crossbeam` crate to implement a concurrent hash table:

```rust
use std::collections::HashMap;
use std::sync::{Arc, Mutex, Condvar};
use crossbeam::thread;

struct ConcurrentHashMap {
    map: Arc<Mutex<HashMap<String, String>>>,
    condvar: Arc<Condvar>,
}

impl ConcurrentHashMap {
    fn new() -> Self {
        let map = Arc::new(Mutex::new(HashMap::new()));
        let condvar = Arc::new(Condvar::new());
        ConcurrentHashMap { map, condvar }
    }

    fn put(&self, key: String, value: String) {
        let mut guard = self.map.lock().unwrap();
        guard.insert(key, value);
        self.condvar.notify_all();
    }
}

fn main() {
    let map = ConcurrentHashMap::new();
    let threads: Vec<_> = (0..5).map(|i| {
        let map = map.clone();
        thread::spawn(move || {
            for j in 0..10 {
                let key = format!("key-{}-{}", i, j);
                let value = format!("value-{}-{}", i, j);
                map.put(key, value);
            }
        })
    }).collect();

    for thread in threads {
        thread.join().unwrap();
    }

    let guard = map.map.lock().unwrap();
    let size = guard.len();
    println!("Hash table size: {}", size);
}
```

In this example, we create a `ConcurrentHashMap` instance that contains an `Arc` to a `Mutex<HashMap<String, String>>` and an `Arc` to a `Condvar`. The `put` function allows threads to add key-value pairs to the hash table safely, by acquiring a lock on the `Mutex` before inserting the pair and notifying waiting threads using the `Condvar`. 

We use the `crossbeam::thread` module to create five threads that add a total of 50 key-value pairs to the hash table. After all threads have finished running, we print the final size of the hash table to verify that all pairs were added correctly.

This is just one example of how the crossbeam crate can be used to implement concurrent data structures in Rust. With its low-level synchronization primitives and high-level abstractions, the crate is a powerful tool for building efficient and safe concurrent programs.

pthread_attr_setschedpolicy and sched_setscheduler are two different functions used in Linux for setting the scheduling policy of threads. The main difference between them is that pthread_attr_setschedpolicy is used to set the scheduling policy for a thread attribute object, while sched_setscheduler is used to set the scheduling policy for a running thread.

pthread_attr_setschedpolicy:
pthread_attr_setschedpolicy is a function that sets the scheduling policy attribute value of the thread attribute object referenced by the attr parameter. This attribute value will be used by the pthread_create function when a new thread is created. The scheduling policy determines how the operating system schedules a thread to run on the CPU.

sched_setscheduler:
sched_setscheduler is a function that sets the scheduling policy and scheduling parameters for a running thread. The parameters are specified in the sched_param structure. The scheduling policy and parameters determine how the operating system schedules the thread to run on the CPU.

Example:

```c
#include <pthread.h>
#include <sched.h>

void *thread_func(void *arg) {
    // thread code
}

int main() {
    pthread_t thread;
    pthread_attr_t attr; 

    // Create thread attribute object
    pthread_attr_init(&attr);

    // Set scheduling policy for attribute object
    pthread_attr_setschedpolicy(&attr, SCHED_FIFO);

    // Create thread with attribute
    pthread_create(&thread, &attr, thread_func, NULL);

    // Set scheduling policy for running thread
    struct sched_param param;
    param.sched_priority = 1;
    sched_setscheduler(thread, SCHED_FIFO, &param);

    // Wait for thread to finish
    pthread_join(thread, NULL);

    return 0;
}
```

In the above example, we first create a thread attribute object and set its scheduling policy using pthread_attr_setschedpolicy. Then we create a new thread using this attribute object. Later, we set the scheduling policy and parameters for the running thread using sched_setscheduler. Finally, we wait for the thread to finish using pthread_join. This example shows how to use both functions to set the scheduling policy for a thread.

The main difference between the two functions `pthread_attr_setschedpolicy()` and `sched_setscheduler()` is that the first is used for setting the scheduling policy for a new pthread, whereas the second one is used for setting the scheduling policy for an existing thread or process.

Here's a simple illustration of both the functions in the same C program:

```c
#include <pthread.h>
#include <sched.h>
#include <stdio.h>
#include <unistd.h>

void *thread_function(void *arg) {
  printf("Thread started\n");
  sleep(1);
  printf("Thread end\n");
  return NULL;
}

int main() {
  pthread_t thread;
  pthread_attr_t attr;
  struct sched_param param;

  // Set the scheduling policy and priority for the newly created pthread
  pthread_attr_init(&attr);
  pthread_attr_setschedpolicy(&attr, SCHED_FIFO);
  param.sched_priority = 10;
  pthread_attr_setschedparam(&attr, &param);

  // Create the pthread with the specified SCHED_FIFO policy and priority 10
  if (pthread_create(&thread, &attr, thread_function, NULL) != 0) {
    perror("pthread_create");
    return 1;
  }

  // Set the scheduling policy and priority for the main thread or process
  param.sched_priority = 20;
  if (sched_setscheduler(getpid(), SCHED_RR, &param) != 0) {
    perror("sched_setscheduler");
    return 1;
  }

  printf("Main started\n");
  // Now join the pthread
  pthread_join(thread, NULL);
  printf("Main end\n");
  return 0;
}
```

In this C program, we're setting up a new pthread_attr_t object and using that attr object with the `pthread_create()` function to create a separately scheduled thread. We use `pthread_attr_setschedpolicy()` to set the scheduling policy for the new thread.

For the main thread (the process itself), we use `sched_setscheduler()` to set the scheduling policy and priority directly. Note that the main thread will continue with the default scheduling policy and priority if we don't change it with `sched_setscheduler()`. The `getpid()` function is used to get the process ID (or thread ID, in the case of the main thread).

In the C program below, a thread is created, and you can change the priority of the thread using command line arguments.

```c
#include <pthread.h>
#include <sched.h>
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>
#include <unistd.h>

void *thread_function(void *arg) {
  printf("Thread started\n");
  sleep(1);
  printf("Thread end\n");
  return NULL;
}

int main(int argc, char *argv[]) {
  pthread_t thread;
  pthread_attr_t attr;
  struct sched_param param;

  if (argc < 2) {
    printf("Usage: %s <priority>\n", argv[0]);
    return 1;
  }

  int priority = atoi(argv[1]);

  // Set the scheduling policy and priority for the newly created pthread
  pthread_attr_init(&attr);
  pthread_attr_setschedpolicy(&attr, SCHED_FIFO);
  param.sched_priority = priority;
  pthread_attr_setschedparam(&attr, &param);

  // Create the pthread with the specified SCHED_FIFO policy and priority
  if (pthread_create(&thread, &attr, thread_function, NULL) != 0) {
    perror("pthread_create");
    return 1;
  }

  printf("Main started\n");
  // Now join the pthread
  pthread_join(thread, NULL);
  printf("Main end\n");
  return 0;
}
```

To compile and run the program:

1. Save the above code to a file named `change_thread_priority.c`.
2. Open a terminal and navigate to the file's location.
3. Compile the program using: `gcc change_thread_priority.c -o change_thread_priority -lpthread`
4. Run the program with a priority of your choice: `./change_thread_priority 10`

Please note that on some systems, you may need to run the program with root privileges in order to set realtime scheduling policies (SCHED_FIFO or SCHED_RR) and high priorities. In this case, you can run the program using `sudo`:

```sh
sudo ./change_thread_priority 10
```

Здравствуйте! Вот пример функции на C, которая принимает массив, второй массив принимает значение первого и возвращается из функции:

```c
#include <stdio.h>

int* copy_array(int arr[], int size) {
    int* copy = malloc(size * sizeof(int));
    for (int i = 0; i < size; i++) {
        copy[i] = arr[i];
    }
    return copy;
}

int main() {
    int array1[] = {1, 2, 3, 4, 5};
    int* array2 = copy_array(array1, 5);
    for (int i = 0; i < 5; i++) {
        printf("%d ", array2[i]);
    }
    printf("\n");
    free(array2);
    return 0;
}
```

Здесь функция `copy_array` создает копию переданного массива `arr` размером `size`, используя динамическую память. Эта копия возвращается из функции. В функции `main` создается массив `array1`, затем создается его копия `array2` с помощью вызова `copy_array`. Затем `array2` выводится на экран и освобождается память, выделенная для этого массива.

Конечно, вот пример функции на C, которая принимает массив типа char, создает его копию и возвращает ее для использования в другой функции:

```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>
#include <string.h>

char* copy_string(char str[]) {
    int len = strlen(str);
    char* copy = malloc(len + 1);
    strncpy(copy, str, len);
    return copy;
}

int main() {
    char string1[] = "Hello, world!";
    char* string2 = copy_string(string1);
    printf("string1: %s\n", string1);
    printf("string2: %s\n", string2);
    free(string2);
    return 0;
}
```

В этом примере функция `copy_string` принимает строку типа `char` `str`, создает ее копию с помощью функции `malloc` и `strncpy`, и возвращает эту копию. Функция `main` определяет строку `string1`, затем выполняет копирование с помощью вызова `copy_string`. Затем обе строки выводятся на экран и освобождается память, выделенная для строки `string2`.

